<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Jones, John. Letter to Judge Adam Mabane, 1787, with a copy of Jones's testimony 1783. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0003</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">that the testimony I gave upon the Proceedings in the Cause or Action of Jenkin Williams Esq<sup>r</sup> Solicitor for General Haldimand against the Honble John Cochrane is <span style="text-decoration:underline;">contrary to the Records and therefore contrary to Truth</span>.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">This, Sir, is a heavy charge declaring me guilty of a very heinous offence; it is my duty to prove my innocence, in doing which, if I shall unavoidably be led to recriminate, I shall stand acquitted by the World.  On the principle of recrimination, it is fair to retort, and to turn the accusation upon my Adversary; I fear not that I shall succeed by what I shall now offer to the perusal of the Public.</p>
<p class="head">My Testimony states</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">That, I saw M<sup>r</sup> Judge Mabane take out of his pocket a written paper, which he brought with him into Court, containing an Order, or Entry, or Judgement on the motion which M<sup>r</sup> Williams Solicitor for the plaintiff had made the preceeding Court day being four days before;</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">That, M<sup>r</sup> Panet, Advocate for the Defendant M<sup>r</sup> Cochrane, had prepared his Clients Defence, containing </p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">his objections against the said motion of M<sup>r</sup> Williams, &amp; shewing Cause why the Court should not grant it;</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">JJ</p>

